<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">June 19, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Rewrote the flagship dog-breeding-software comparison page to add BreederBuddy as a compared competitor, refresh the H1 for exact-match query alignment, and add a side-by-side pricing table. Initial rewrite shipped with several factual errors about competitor pricing and trial offers; a same-day correction commit replaced every wrong claim with verified facts.</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      <strong>Why.</strong> 28-day GSC pull ending 2026-06-16: <code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> earned 402 impressions and 1 click at average position 16-18 across 14 ranking queries (best dog breeding software, dog breeder software, breeder management software, and ~12 others). The page ranks. The page does not convert. BreederBuddy was the competitor winning the clicks; their homepage runs ~3,500 words and visible pricing at $29.99/mo with a 30-day no-credit-card trial.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What changed.</strong>
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2">
      <li><strong>H1 refreshed</strong> from "The Best Dog Breeding Software in 2026: A Working Breeder&apos;s Comparison" to <em>"The Best Dog Breeding Software in 2026 (Compared by a Real Breeder)"</em>, matching the meta title rewritten earlier on 2026-06-19 and tightening alignment with the head-term query.</li>
      <li><strong>TL;DR rewritten</strong> as a verdict-by-program-size block with anchor links to each vendor section: working program → BreederHQ, single-species dog or cat → BreederBuddy, lowest-price multi-species → Breeder Cloud Pro, dog-only sub-$15/mo → Dog Breeder Pro, hobby → Breedera, pedigree-club → ZooEasy/Kintraks/PedFast.</li>
      <li><strong>BreederBuddy added</strong> to the ItemList schema (n=8), the side-by-side pricing table, the workflow matrix, the individual breakdowns, the "best for by breeder type" section, the mobile experience table, and the pros/cons section.</li>
      <li><strong>New side-by-side table</strong> with publicly verified pricing, trial length, species count, buyer portal, public marketplace status, and mobile experience for every vendor.</li>
      <li><strong>Workflow matrix expanded</strong> with three rows that separate the comparison: OFA auto-sync, CHIC readiness by breed, and temperament testing (Volhard PAT, Gun Dog Aptitude, working-dog role suitability).</li>
      <li><strong>Page-specific SoftwareApplication schema added</strong> alongside the existing Article and ItemList schema. FAQPage and BreadcrumbList continue to be auto-emitted by BaseLayout.</li>
      <li><strong>FAQ expanded</strong> from 12 to 14 entries with direct head-to-head "How does BreederHQ compare to BreederBuddy" and "How does BreederHQ compare to Breeder Cloud Pro" answers.</li>
      <li><strong>BreederHQ breakdown deepened</strong> to call out OFA Sync, CHIC Readiness Widget, Volhard PAT, Gun Dog Aptitude scoring, working-dog role suitability, Scout AI document extraction, and the 9-species claim by name.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <strong>Initial rewrite was wrong about four competitor facts. Corrected the same day:</strong>
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
      <li>Claimed BreederHQ had a "no time limit free tier." <strong>False.</strong> BreederHQ has a 14-day free trial. Corrected throughout: schema offer, TL;DR, BreederHQ breakdown, pros/cons, final CTA.</li>
      <li>Claimed BreederBuddy had "no free tier." <strong>False.</strong> BreederBuddy offers a 30-day free trial with no credit card required, which is actually longer than BreederHQ&apos;s. Corrected throughout.</li>
      <li>Claimed Breeder Cloud Pro had "no public marketplace." <strong>False.</strong> Breeder Cloud Pro operates a public "Find a Breeder" directory at breedercloudpro.com/breeders plus a Pet Portal (Match). Corrected to "directory, not a listing marketplace" framing.</li>
      <li>Claimed Dog Breeder Pro pricing was "unpublished/gated." <strong>False.</strong> Dog Breeder Pro pricing is publicly posted: $8.49/mo Standard ($84.99/year) or $14.99/mo Premium ($149.99/year) with a 30-day no-credit-card trial. Corrected throughout.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <strong>What didn&apos;t change.</strong> No invented BreederHQ customer numbers (BreederBuddy is leading with placeholder-looking "0+" stats; we declined to compete on fake metrics). No "verified breeder" or "verified directory" language. No em dashes. Existing Article schema preserved with bumped <code>dateModified</code>. Existing workflow visual, "what makes great dog breeding software" rubric, and decision rubric all preserved.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Honest competitive frame:</strong> BreederHQ&apos;s real differentiators (verified): nine species in one account, integrated buyer-facing listing marketplace at marketplace.breederhq.com, OFA Sync that auto-pulls public results, CHIC Readiness Widget, Volhard PAT + Gun Dog Aptitude scoring, working-dog role suitability analysis, Scout AI document extraction, multi-point progesterone timing as a primary workflow, and iOS + Android native apps. None of those nine differentiators is claimed by BreederBuddy, Breeder Cloud Pro, or Dog Breeder Pro on their public sites.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What does NOT differentiate BreederHQ that I initially claimed it did:</strong> free trial (BreederHQ&apos;s 14 days is the shortest in this comparison; BreederBuddy, Breeder Cloud Pro, and Dog Breeder Pro all offer 30 days), price transparency (Dog Breeder Pro and Breeder Cloud Pro post public pricing too), public buyer-side visibility in absolute terms (Breeder Cloud Pro has a directory, even if it&apos;s not a transactional marketplace).
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Success criteria at 4 weeks.</strong> GSC: average position 16-18 → 8-12 across the 14 ranking queries; clicks-per-week from &lt;1 to 5-10. If both move, depth-and-comparison was the right play. If neither moves, the problem is domain authority and a different lever is required.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>
